            <td>4.1/5</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: Adjustable Aluminum Laptop Stand</h2>
      <p>This stand won because it was the only model in our comparison that delivered both genuine ergonomic lift and measurable cooling without any wobble. The seven-level height adjustment ranges from 5.5 to 7.5 inches, which covers eye-level positioning for users between 5'7" and 6'1" on a standard 29-inch desk. Most fixed-height stands land either too low for taller users or too high for shorter ones. The aluminum alloy construction supports up to 44 pounds — far beyond any laptop — and the open-frame design means there is nothing blocking the laptop's intake vents.</p>
      <p>The cooling benefit is real and measurable. According to manufacturer specifications and thermal design analysis, internal temperatures can drop by up to 9 degrees when using this stand with a 15-inch gaming laptop, keeping the CPU below throttle and sustaining higher clock speeds. A 14-inch MacBook Pro sees a smaller but still meaningful 5-degree drop. The aluminum frame itself acts as a passive heatsink, drawing heat away from the chassis contact points. Plastic stands show only 2-3 degrees of improvement because they insulate rather than conduct.</p>
      <p>The folding design collapses to 0.4 inches thick, which is thin enough to slide into a laptop sleeve alongside the computer. The universal fit accommodates devices from a 10-inch iPad to a 17-inch gaming laptop, with rubber grips on the support arms preventing any sliding during typing. The one weakness: the hinge adjustment requires two hands and a bit of force, so it is not something you will reconfigure multiple times a day. Set it once to your height and leave it.</p>

      <div class="product-box">
        <h2>Adjustable Aluminum Laptop Stand</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>7-level height adjustment</strong> — eye level from 5.5" to 7.5" for 5'7" to 6'1" users</li>
          <li><strong>Aluminum alloy build</strong> — dissipates heat, supports up to 44 lbs</li>
          <li><strong>Universal fit</strong> — 10" to 17" laptops, MacBook to gaming rigs</li>
          <li><strong>Ventilated open design</strong> — 9C thermal drop vs flat on desk</li>
          <li><strong>Foldable & portable</strong> — 0.4 inches thick when folded, sleeve-ready</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=adjustable+laptop+stand+aluminum&tag=toolwise20-20" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Check Current Price on Amazon</a>
      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Roost Laptop Stand v3</h2>
      <p>If portability is your priority and you want to spend under $20, the Roost v3 is the travel-focused value pick. It folds to a thicker but still pocketable form, weighs only a few ounces, and raises the laptop to a comparable eye-level height. The fiberglass-reinforced plastic is surprisingly rigid for its weight, and is rated to support a 14-inch MacBook without noticeable flex. The setup and breakdown are faster than the aluminum stand, making it better for users who pack up daily.</p>
      <p>The tradeoffs are cooling and capacity. The plastic construction provides only 2-3 degrees of thermal improvement versus the aluminum stand's 5-9 degrees, and the weight rating is lower — it is not recommended for heavy 17-inch gaming laptops. The height is not adjustable across multiple levels; you get one height per configuration, though flipping the stand changes it. For travel and light laptops, the Roost is excellent. For a permanent desk setup with a heavy laptop, the aluminum stand is worth the extra $10.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The first question is whether you will use an external keyboard and mouse. If yes, get a stand that raises the laptop to eye level — that is the entire ergonomic benefit. If no, and you plan to type on the raised laptop, do not buy a tall stand; you will wreck your shoulders and wrists within a week. For typing on the laptop, use a low-profile stand (1-2 inches) that improves cooling without raising the keyboard to an unusable angle. The eye-level stands only make sense paired with external input devices.</p>
      <p>Material matters more than marketing suggests. Aluminum stands cool passively because the metal conducts heat away from the laptop chassis, while plastic stands insulate and provide only the airflow benefit. If your laptop runs hot or throttles under load, aluminum is worth the premium. If you only need ergonomic lift and your laptop runs cool, plastic is fine and lighter for travel. According to manufacturer specifications, the thermal difference is 5-9 degrees for aluminum versus 2-3 degrees for plastic under sustained load.</p>
      <p>Finally, check the weight rating against your actual laptop. A 13-inch MacBook Air weighs 2.7 pounds and any stand will hold it. A 17-inch gaming laptop can weigh 6-7 pounds, and flimsy stands will flex, wobble during typing, or eventually fail at the hinges. Look for a rating of at least 2x your laptop's weight to account for typing force and accidental bumps. The aluminum stand's 44-pound rating is overkill for most laptops, which is exactly what you want — a stand that never makes you wonder if it will hold.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Does a laptop stand actually improve cooling?</summary>
          <p>Yes, by 5-10C according to manufacturer specifications. Laptops draw air from the bottom, and a flat desk blocks intake. An open-frame stand lifts the laptop and allows unrestricted airflow, and aluminum models also act as a passive heatsink. Active fan stands add another 2-3C of cooling but are noisier.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What height should a laptop stand raise the screen to?</summary>
          <p>The top of the screen should sit at or just below eye level when you are sitting with good posture. For most people on a standard desk, that means raising the laptop 5 to 7 inches. You will need an external keyboard and mouse, since typing on a raised laptop is ergonomically wrong.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Can I use a laptop stand with a 17-inch gaming laptop?</summary>
          <p>Yes, but check the weight rating. Heavy 17-inch gaming laptops can exceed 6 lbs, and flimsy stands flex or tip. Look for an aluminum stand rated for at least 10 lbs, and verify the support arms are wide enough to grip the laptop's rubber feet without covering the vents.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

